Tesla early Tuesday raised prices on all its vehicles in the United States — two days after CEO Elon Musk said on Twitter that the auto company and his SpaceX business were feeling the pressure of inflation. Tesla & SpaceX are seeing significant recent inflation pressure in raw materials & logistics— Elon Musk (@elonmusk) March 14, 2022 The company raised prices on all of its cars in the United States and on its Model 3 and Model Y vehicles in China. Nickel is one material used in electric vehicle batteries that has risen in price. Tesla’s cheapest electric car, the Model 3, has a new starting price of $47,000, representing an increase of about $2,000, according to a report in electrek, a news website that covers electric transportation and sustainable energy. Last week, Tesla put in place its first price increase of the year, charging an additional $1,000 for all vehicles equipped with long-range battery packs. Meanwhile, Tesla has been purchasing aluminum from a Russian company (Rusal) since 2020, according to CNBC. The report said that there’s no indication that Musk’s company has ceased doing business with Rusal since Russia invaded Ukraine in late February. 